<!--StartFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal">For those of you whom I may not have met, my name is Ciera Martinez.  I am a recent PhD graduate from the UC Davis Plant Biology department and began working as a post doc in Mike’s lab in January.</p><p class="MsoNormal">Really quickly I want tell  you a little about my past research interests. </p><p class="MsoNormal">Overall all my research was in plant evolutionary development, specifically leaf development, with a little bit of flower development thrown in. I was very interested in how plants get their shape. For instance using elliptical forier analysis on many many leaf outlines. </p><p class="MsoNormal">My work was also very embedded into hormone transport, particularly auxin, the coolest hormone ever, </p><p class="MsoNormal"><br></p><p class="MsoNormal">And lastly I was interested in transcriptomics, specifically asking the question what genes are expressed during early leaf development that regulate cell differentiation.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><br></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<!--EndFragment-->
